HEADWORD: phthisis
<hw>phthi"sis</hw> <pr>(th⟦imac⟧"s⟦icr⟧s; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L., fr. Gr. <grk>fqi`sis</grk>, fr. <grk>fqi`ein</grk> to pass or
waste away: cf. F. <ets>phthisie</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A
wasting or consumption of the tissues. The term is now obsolete; it was
once applied to many wasting diseases, but in the early 1900's became
restricted to tuberculosis of the lungs (pulmonary phthisis, or
consumption). See <er>Consumption</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fibroid phthisis</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Fibroid</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

